# 5. Kubernetes and Container FinOps

For Amazon EKS:

## Cluster Optimization

### Use Cluster Autoscaler/Karpenter

[Karpenter](https://karpenter.sh/?utm_source=chatgpt.com) can:

* provision right-sized nodes dynamically
* improve Spot utilization
* reduce idle capacity

### Bin Packing

Reduce:

* underutilized nodes
* fragmented workloads

### Namespace-Level Cost Allocation

Use:

* Kubecost
* OpenCost

Tools:

* [Kubecost](https://www.kubecost.com/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)
* [OpenCost](https://opencost.io/?utm_source=chatgpt.com)

---

# 6. Database Cost Optimization

## RDS

### Rightsize Databases

Look for:

* low CPU
* low connections
* oversized memory

### Storage Optimization

* use gp3
* enable autoscaling carefully
* reduce backup retention if policy allows

### Aurora Serverless

Good for:

* variable workloads
* intermittent traffic

---

## DynamoDB

Optimize:

* read/write capacity
* hot partitions
* unused GSIs

Use:

* On-demand for unpredictable traffic
* Provisioned + autoscaling for stable workloads

---

# 7. Network and Data Transfer Optimization

Data transfer is often overlooked.

## Reduce Cross-AZ Traffic

Especially expensive in:

* microservices
* Kubernetes clusters

Strategies:

* co-locate services
* minimize chatty architectures

---

## Use CloudFront

Amazon CloudFront reduces:

* origin bandwidth
* latency
* transfer costs

---

## NAT Gateway Optimization

NAT Gateways can become major hidden costs.

Alternatives:

* VPC endpoints
* Gateway endpoints
* PrivateLink

---

# 8. Governance and Automation

## Policy Enforcement

Use:

* AWS Config
* SCPs
* Service Catalog

Examples:

* deny expensive instance types
* prevent public snapshots
* require tags

---

## Automated Cost Controls

Examples:

* auto-delete idle resources
* detect anomalies
* stop zombie workloads

Services:

* Cost Anomaly Detection
* EventBridge
* Lambda

